  "stem": "<p>For the linear function <i>g</i>, the graph of <i>y</i> = <i>g</i>(<i>x</i>) in the <i>xy</i>-plane has a slope of 4 and a <i>y</i>-intercept at (0, &minus;3). Which equation defines <i>g</i>?</p>",
  "answerOptions": [
    {
      "id": "a",
      "content": "<p><i>g</i>(<i>x</i>) = 4<i>x</i> &minus; 3</p>"
    },
    {
      "id": "b",
      "content": "<p><i>g</i>(<i>x</i>) = &minus;4<i>x</i> &minus; 3</p>"
    },
    {
      "id": "c",
      "content": "<p><i>g</i>(<i>x</i>) = (1/4)<i>x</i> &minus; 3</p>"
    },
    {
      "id": "d",
      "content": "<p><i>g</i>(<i>x</i>) = 4<i>x</i> + 3</p>"
    }
  ],
  "keys": [
    "a"
  ],
  "rationale": "<p>Choice A is correct. Using slope-intercept form <i>g</i>(<i>x</i>) = <i>m</i><i>x</i> + <i>b</i> with <i>m</i> = 4 and <i>b</i> = &minus;3 gives <i>g</i>(<i>x</i>) = 4<i>x</i> &minus; 3.</p><p>Other choices have wrong slope or wrong sign on the intercept.</p>",
